# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slo-burn-rate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] From their conception, large chemical, refining, power generation, and other processing plants required the use of a control system to keep the process operating successfully and producing products.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Due to the fragility of the components as compared to the process, these control systems often required a control room to protect them from the elements and process conditions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] In the early days of control rooms, they used what were referred to as "panel boards" which were loaded with control instruments and indicators.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] These were tied to sensors located in the process streams and on the outside of process equipment.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The sensors relayed their information to the control instruments via analogue signals, such as a 4-20 mA current loop in the form of twisted pair wiring.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] At first these systems merely yielded information, and a well-trained operator was required to make adjustments either by changing flow rates, or altering energy inputs to keep the process within its designed limits.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Alarms were added to alert the operator to a condition that was about to exceed a design limit, or had already exceeded a design limit.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Additionally, shutdown systems were employed to halt a process that was in danger of exceeding either safety, environmental or monetarily acceptable process limits.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Alarm were indicated to the operator by annunciator horns, and lights of different colours.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] (For instance, green lights meant OK, Yellow meant not OK, and Red meant BAD.) Panel boards were usually laid out in a manner that replicated the process flow in the plant.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] So instrumentation indicating operating units with the plant was grouped together for recognition sake and ease of problem solution.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] It was a simple matter to look at the entire panel board, and discern whether any section of the plant was running poorly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] This was due to both the design of the instruments and the implementation of the alarms associated with the instruments.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Instrumentation companies put a lot of effort into the design and individual layout of the instruments they manufactured.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] To do this they employed behavioural psychology practices which revealed how much information a human being could collect in a quick glance.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] More complex plants had more complex panel boards, and therefore often more human operators or controllers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Thus, in the early days of panel board systems, alarms were regulated by both size and cost.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] In essence, they were limited by the amount of available board space, and the cost of running wiring, and hooking up an annunciator (horn), indicator (light) and switches to flip to acknowledge, and clear a resolved alarm.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] It was often the case that if a new alarm was needed, an old one had to be given up.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] As technology developed, the control system and control methods were tasked to continue to advance a higher degree of plant automation with each passing year.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Highly complex material processing called for highly complex control methodologies.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Also, global competition pushed manufacturing operations to increase production while using less energy, and producing less waste.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Around the mid 80's, we entered the digital revolution.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Distributed control systems (DCS) were a boon to the industry.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The engineer could now control the process without having to understand the equipment necessary to perform the control functions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Panel boards were no longer required, because all of the information that once came across analogue instruments could be digitised, stuffed into a computer and manipulated to achieve the same control actions once performed with amplifiers and potentiometers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] As a side effect, that also meant that alarms were easy and cheap to configure and deploy.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] You simply typed in a location, a value to alarm on and set it to active.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The unintended result was that soon people alarmed everything.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Initial installers set an alarm at 80% and 20% of the operating range of any variable just as a habit.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The integration of programmable logic controllers, safety instrumented systems, and packaged equipment controllers has been accompanied by an overwhelming increase in associated alarms.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] One other unfortunate part of the digital revolution was that what once covered several square yards of panel space, now had to be fit into a 17-inch computer monitor.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Multiple pages of information was thus employed to replicate the information on the replaced panel board.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Alarms were used to tell an operator to go look at a page he was not viewing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Alarms were used to tell an operator that a tank was filling.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Every mistake made in operations usually resulted in a new alarm.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] With the implementation of the OSHA 1910 regulations, HAZOPS studies usually requested several new alarms.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Incidents began to accrue as a combination of too much data collided with too little useful information.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Recognizing that alarms were becoming a problem, industrial control system users banded together and formed the Alarm Management Task Force, which was a customer advisory board led by Honeywell in 1990.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The AMTF included participants from chemical, petrochemical, and refining operations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] They gathered and wrote a document on the issues associated with alarm management.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] This group quickly realised that alarm problems were simply a subset of a larger problem, and formed the Abnormal Situation Management Consortium (ASM is a registered trademark of Honeywell).
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium Archived 2008-09-07 at the Wayback Machine developed a research proposal and was granted funding from the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) in 1994.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The focus of this work was addressing the complex human-system interaction and factors that influence successful performance for process operators.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Automation solutions have often been developed without consideration of the human that needs to interact with the solution.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] In particular, alarms are intended to improve situation awareness for the control room operator, but a poorly configured alarm system does not achieve this goal.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium has produced documents on best practices in alarm management, as well as operator situation awareness, operator effectiveness, and other operator-oriented issues.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] These documents were originally for ASM Consortium members only, but the ASMC has recently offered these documents publicly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The ASM consortium also participated in development of an alarm management guideline published by the Engineering Equipment & Materials Users' Association (EEMUA) in the UK.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium provided data from their member companies, and contributed to the editing of the guideline.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] The result is EEMUA 191 "Alarm Systems- A Guide to Design, Management and Procurement".
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Several institutions and societies are producing standards on alarm management to assist their members in the best practices use of alarms in industrial manufacturing systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Among them are the ISA (ISA 18.2), API (API 1167) and NAMUR (Namur NA 102).
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Several companies also offer software packages to assist users in dealing with alarm management issues.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alarm-management] Among them are DCS manufacturing companies, and third-party vendors who offer add-on systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] This chapter explains how to turn your SLOs into actionable alerts on significant events.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Both our first SRE book and this book talk about implementing SLOs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We believe that having good SLOs that measure the reliability of your platform, as experienced by your customers, provides the highest-quality indication for when an on-call engineer should respond.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Here we give specific guidance on how to turn those SLOs into alerting rules so that you can respond to problems before you consume too much of your error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Our examples present a series of increasingly complex implementations for alerting metrics and logic; we discuss the utility and shortcomings of each.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] While our examples use a simple request-driven service and Prometheus syntax, you can apply this approach in any alerting framework.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In order to generate alerts from service level indicators (SLIs) and an error budget, you need a way to combine these two elements into a specific rule.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Your goal is to be notified for a significant event: an event that consumes a large fraction of the error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Constructing alert rules for your SLOs can become quite complex.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Here we present six ways to configure alerting on significant events, in order of increasing fidelity, to arrive at an option that offers good control over the four parameters of precision, recall, detection time, and reset time simultaneously.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Each of the following approaches addresses a different problem, and some eventually solve multiple problems at the same time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The first three nonviable attempts work toward the latter three viable alerting strategies, with approach 6 being the most viable and most highly recommended option.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The first method is simple to implement but inadequate, while the optimal method provides a complete solution to defend an SLO over both the long and the short term.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For the purposes of this discussion, “error budgets” and “error rates” apply to all SLIs, not just those with “error” in their name.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In the section What to Measure: Using SLIs, we recommend using SLIs that capture the ratio of good events to total events.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The error budget gives the number of allowed bad events, and the error rate is the ratio of bad events to total events.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For the most trivial solution, you can choose a small time window (for example, 10 minutes) and alert if the error rate over that window exceeds the SLO.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Figure 5-1 shows the relationship between detection time and error rate for an example service with an alert window of 10 minutes and a 99.9% SLO.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-1 shows the benefits and disadvantages of alerting when the immediate error rate is too high.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We can build upon the preceding example by changing the size of the alert window to improve precision.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] By increasing the window size, you spend a higher budget amount before triggering an alert.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-2 shows the benefits and disadvantages of alerting when the error rate is too high over a larger window of time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Figure 5-2 shows that while the error rate over a 36-hour period has fallen to a negligible level, the 36-hour average error rate remains above the threshold.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Most monitoring systems allow you to add a duration parameter to the alert criteria so the alert won’t fire unless the value remains above the threshold for some time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-3 shows the benefits and disadvantages of using a duration parameter for alerts.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Figure 5-3 shows the average error rate over a 5-minute window of a service with a 10-minute duration before the alert fires.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] A series of 100% error spikes lasting 5 minutes every 10 minutes never triggers an alert, despite consuming 35% of the error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Each spike consumed almost 12% of the 30-day budget, yet the alert never triggered.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] To improve upon the previous solution, you want to create an alert with good detection time and high precision.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] To this end, you can introduce a burn rate to reduce the size of the window while keeping the alert budget spend constant.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Burn rate is how fast, relative to the SLO, the service consumes the error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Figure 5-4 shows the relationship between burn rates and error budgets.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The example service uses a burn rate of 1, which means that it’s consuming error budget at a rate that leaves you with exactly 0 budget at the end of the SLO’s time window (see Chapter 4 in our first book).
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] With an SLO of 99.9% over a time window of 30 days, a constant 0.1% error rate uses exactly all of the error budget: a burn rate of 1.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-4 shows burn rates, their corresponding error rates, and the time it takes to exhaust the SLO budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] By keeping the alert window fixed at one hour and deciding that a 5% error budget spend is significant enough to notify someone, you can derive the burn rate to use for the alert.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Five percent of a 30-day error budget spend over one hour requires a burn rate of 36.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-5 shows the benefits and limitations of alerting based on burn rate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Your alerting logic can use multiple burn rates and time windows, and fire alerts when burn rates surpass a specified threshold.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] This option retains the benefits of alerting on burn rates and ensures that you don’t overlook lower (but still significant) error rates.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] It’s also a good idea to set up ticket notifications for incidents that typically go unnoticed but can exhaust your error budget if left unchecked—for example, a 10% budget consumption in three days.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] This rate of errors catches significant events, but since the rate of budget consumption provides adequate time to address the event, you don’t need to page someone.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We recommend 2% budget consumption in one hour and 5% budget consumption in six hours as reasonable starting numbers for paging, and 10% budget consumption in three days as a good baseline for ticket alerts.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The appropriate numbers depend on the service and the baseline page load.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For busier services, and depending on on-call responsibilities over weekends and holidays, you may want ticket alerts for the six-hour window.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-6 shows the corresponding burn rates and time windows for percentages of SLO budget consumed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Figure 5-5 shows the detection time and alert type according to the error rate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Multiple burn rates allow you to adjust the alert to give appropriate priority based on how quickly you have to respond.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If an issue will exhaust the error budget within hours or a few days, sending an active notification is appropriate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-7 lists the benefits and disadvantages of using multiple burn rates.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We can enhance the multi-burn-rate alerts in iteration 5 to notify us only when we’re still actively burning through the budget—thereby reducing the number of false positives.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] To do this, we need to add another parameter: a shorter window to check if the error budget is still being consumed as we trigger the alert.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] A good guideline is to make the short window 1/12 the duration of the long window, as shown in Figure 5-6.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The graph shows both alerting threshold.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] After experiencing 15% errors for 10 minutes, the short window average goes over the alerting threshold immediately, and the long window average goes over the threshold after 5 minutes, at which point the alert starts firing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The short window average drops below the threshold 5 minutes after the errors stop, at which point the alert stops firing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The long window average drops below the threshold 60 minutes after the errors stop.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For example, you can send a page-level alert when you exceed the 14.4x burn rate over both the previous one hour and the previous five minutes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We recommend the parameters listed in Table 5-8 as the starting point for your SLO-based alerting configuration.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We have found that alerting based on multiple burn rates is a powerful way to implement SLO-based alerting.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-9 shows the benefits and limitations of using multiple burn rates and window sizes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The multiwindow, multi-burn-rate approach just detailed works well when a sufficiently high rate of incoming requests provides a meaningful signal when an issue arises.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] However, these approaches can cause problems for systems that receive a low rate of requests.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If a system has either a low number of users or natural low-traffic periods (such as nights and weekends), you may need to alter your approach.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] It’s harder to automatically distinguish unimportant events in low-traffic services.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For example, if a system receives 10 requests per hour, then a single failed request results in an hourly error rate of 10%.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For a 99.9% SLO, this request constitutes a 1,000x burn rate and would page immediately, as it consumed 13.9% of the 30-day error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] This scenario allows for only seven failed requests in 30 days.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Single requests can fail for a large number of ephemeral and uninteresting reasons that aren’t necessarily cost-effective to solve in the same way as large systematic outages.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The best solution depends on the nature of the service: what is the impact3 of a single failed request?
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] A high-availability target may be appropriate if failed requests are one-off, high-value requests that aren’t retried.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] It may make sense from a business perspective to investigate every single failed request.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] However, in this case, the alerting system notifies you of an error too late.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] A system can synthesize user activity to check for potential errors and high-latency requests.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In the absence of real users, your monitoring system can detect synthetic errors and requests, so your on-call engineers can respond to issues before they impact too many actual users.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Artificial traffic provides more signals to work with, and allows you to reuse your existing monitoring logic and SLO values.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] You may even already have most of the necessary traffic-generating components, such as black-box probers and integration tests.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Generating artificial load does have some downsides.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Most services that warrant SRE support are complex, and have a large system control surface.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Ideally, the system should be designed and built for monitoring using artificial traffic.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Even for a nontrivial service, you can synthesize only a small portion of the total number of user request types.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For a stateful service, the greater number of states exacerbates this problem.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Additionally, if an issue affects real users but doesn’t affect artificial traffic, the successful artificial requests hide the real user signal, so you aren’t notified that users see errors.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If multiple low-traffic services contribute to one overall function, combining their requests into a single higher-level group can detect significant events more precisely and with fewer false positives.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For this approach to work, the services must be related in some way—you can combine microservices that form part of the same product, or multiple request types handled by the same binary.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] A downside to combining services is that a complete failure of an individual service may not count as a significant event.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] You can increase the likelihood that a failure will affect the group as a whole by choosing services with a shared failure domain, such as a common backend database.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] You can still use longer-period alerts that eventually catch these 100% failures for individual services.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Alerting on significant events aims to provide sufficient notice to mitigate problems before they exhaust the entire error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If you can’t adjust the monitoring to be less sensitive to ephemeral events, and generating synthetic traffic is impractical, you might instead consider changing the service to reduce the user impact of a single failed request.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] These changes are useful for high-traffic systems, but even more so for low-traffic systems: they allow for more failed events in the error budget, more signal from monitoring, and more time to respond to an incident before it becomes significant.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] You might also want to reconsider if the impact of a single failure on the error budget accurately reflects its impact on users.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If a small number of errors causes you to lose error budget, do you really need to page an engineer to fix the issue immediately?
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If not, users would be equally happy with a lower SLO.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] With a lower SLO, an engineer is notified only of a larger sustained outage.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Lowering the SLO does have a downside: it involves a product decision.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Changing the SLO affects other aspects of the system, such as expectations around system behavior and when to enact the error budget policy.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] These other requirements may be more important to the product than avoiding some number of low-signal alerts.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In a similar manner, increasing the time window used for the alerting logic ensures alerts that trigger pages are more significant and worthy of attention.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Services with an extremely low or an extremely high availability goal may require special consideration.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For example, consider a service that has a 90% availability target.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Table 5-8 says to page when 2% of the error budget in a single hour is consumed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Because a 100% outage consumes only 1.4% of the budget in that hour, this alert could never fire.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If your error budgets are set over long time periods, you may need to tune your alerting parameters.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For services with an extremely high availability goal, the time to exhaustion for a 100% outage is extremely small.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Even if the alert goes straight to an automated resolution system, the issue may entirely consume the error budget before you can mitigate it.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] Receiving notifications that you have only 26 seconds of budget left isn’t necessarily a bad strategy; it’s just not useful for defending the SLO.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The only way to defend this level of reliability is to design the system so that the chance of a 100% outage is extremely low.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] That way, you can fix issues before consuming the budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] For example, if you initially roll out that change to only 1% of your users, and burn your error budget at the same rate of 1%, you now have 43 minutes before you exhaust your error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] See Canarying Releases for tactics on designing such a system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] When you scale your service, make sure that your alerting strategy is likewise scalable.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] You might be tempted to specify custom alerting parameters for individual services.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If your service comprises 100 microservices (or equivalently, a single service with 100 different request types), this scenario very quickly accumulates toil and cognitive load that does not scale.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In this case, we strongly advise against specifying the alert window and burn rate parameters independently for each service, because doing so quickly becomes overwhelming.5 Once you decide on your alerting parameters, apply them to all your services.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] One technique for managing a large number of SLOs is to group request types into buckets of approximately similar availability requirements.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] By grouping requests rather than placing unique availability and latency objectives on all request types, you can group requests into five buckets, like the example in Table 5-10.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] These buckets provide sufficient fidelity for protecting user happiness, but entail less toil than a system that is more complicated and expensive to manage that probably maps more precisely to the user experience.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] If you set SLOs that are meaningful, understood, and represented in metrics, you can configure alerting to notify an on-caller only when there are actionable, specific threats to the error budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] The techniques for alerting on significant events range from alerting when your error rate goes above your SLO threshold to using multiple levels of burn rate and window sizes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] In most cases, we believe that the multiwindow, multi-burn-rate alerting technique is the most appropriate approach to defending your application’s SLOs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] We hope we have given you the context and tools required to make the right configuration decisions for your own application and organization.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 1Duration clauses can occasionally be useful when you are filtering out ephemeral noise over very short durations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] However, you still need to be aware of the cons listed in this section.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 2As described in the introduction to Site Reliability Engineering, pages and tickets are the only valid ways to get a human to take action.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 3The section What to Measure: Using SLIs recommends a style of SLI that scales according to the impact on the user.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 4See “Overloads and Failure” in Site Reliability Engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 5With the exception of temporary changes to alerting parameters, which are necessary when you’re fixing an ongoing outage and you don’t need to receive notifications during that period.
[src:slo-burn-rate/alerting-on-slos] 6Ninety percent of requests are faster than this threshold.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] A quantity is subject to **exponential decay** if it decreases at a rate proportional to its current value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] where *N*(*t*) is the quantity at time t, *N*0 = *N*(0) is the initial quantity, that is, the quantity at time *t* = 0.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] If the decaying quantity, *N*(*t*), is the number of discrete elements in a certain set, it is possible to compute the average length of time that an element remains in the set.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] and that $\tau$ is the time at which the population of the assembly is reduced to 1⁄*e* ≈ 0.367879441 times its initial value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] For example, if the initial population of the assembly, *N*(0), is 1000, then the population at time $\tau$ , $N(\tau )$ , is 368.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] A very similar equation will be seen below, which arises when the base of the exponential is chosen to be 2, rather than *e*.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] In that case the scaling time is the "half-life".
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] A more intuitive characteristic of exponential decay for many people is the time required for the decaying quantity to fall to one half of its initial value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] (If *N*(*t*) is discrete, then this is the median life-time rather than the mean life-time.) This time is called the *half-life*, and often denoted by the symbol *t*1/2.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Thus, the amount of material left is 2−1 = 1/2 raised to the (whole or fractional) number of half-lives that have passed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Thus, after 3 half-lives there will be 1/23 = 1/8 of the original material left.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] For example, polonium-210 has a half-life of 138 days, and a mean lifetime of 200 days.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] where the final substitution, *N*0 = *e**C*, is obtained by evaluating the equation at *t* = 0, as *N*0 is defined as being the quantity at *t* = 0.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] This is the form of the equation that is most commonly used to describe exponential decay.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Any one of decay constant, mean lifetime, or half-life is sufficient to characterise the decay.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] The notation λ for the decay constant is a remnant of the usual notation for an eigenvalue.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] In this case, λ is the eigenvalue of the negative of the differential operator with *N*(*t*) as the corresponding eigenfunction.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Given an assembly of elements, the number of which decreases ultimately to zero, the **mean lifetime**, $\tau$ , (also called simply the **lifetime**) is the expected value of the amount of time before an object is removed from the assembly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Specifically, if the *individual lifetime* of an element of the assembly is the time elapsed between some reference time and the removal of that element from the assembly, the mean lifetime is the arithmetic mean of the individual lifetimes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Exponential decay is a scalar multiple of the exponential distribution (i.e. the individual lifetime of each object is exponentially distributed), which has a well-known expected value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] We can compute it here using integration by parts.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] A quantity may decay via two or more different processes simultaneously.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] In general, these processes (often called "decay modes", "decay channels", "decay routes" etc.) have different probabilities of occurring, and thus occur at different rates with different half-lives, in parallel.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] The solution to this equation is given in the previous section, where the sum of $\lambda _{1}+\lambda _{2}\,$ is treated as a new total decay constant $\lambda _{c}$ .
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] This is the Harmonic mean of $\tau _{1}$ and $\tau _{2}$ .
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] where $T_{1/2}$ is the combined or total half-life for the process, $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ are so-named **partial half-lives** of corresponding processes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Terms "partial half-life" and "partial mean life" denote quantities derived from a decay constant as if the given decay mode were the only decay mode for the quantity.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] The term "partial half-life" is misleading, because it cannot be measured as a time interval for which a certain quantity is halved.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] In nuclear science and pharmacokinetics, the agent of interest might be situated in a decay chain, where the accumulation is governed by exponential decay of a source agent, while the agent of interest itself decays by means of an exponential process.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] These systems are solved using the Bateman equation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] In the pharmacology setting, some ingested substances might be absorbed into the body by a process reasonably modeled as exponential decay, or might be deliberately formulated to have such a release profile.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Exponential decay occurs in a wide variety of situations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Most of these fall into the domain of the natural sciences.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] Many decay processes that are often treated as exponential, are really only exponential so long as the sample is large and the law of large numbers holds.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] For small samples, a more general analysis is necessary, accounting for a Poisson process.
[src:slo-burn-rate/exponential-decay] , hover over a graph to highlight it and its complement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] In mathematics, a **rate** is the quotient of two quantities, often represented as a fraction.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] In some cases, it may be regarded as a change to a value, which is caused by a change of a value in respect to another value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, acceleration is a change in velocity with respect to time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Rates that have a non-time divisor or denominator include exchange rates, literacy rates, and electric field (in volts per meter).
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] A rate defined using two numbers of the same units will result in a dimensionless quantity, also known as *ratio* or simply as a *rate* (such as tax rates) or counts (such as literacy rate).
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Dimensionless rates can be expressed as a percentage (for example, the global literacy rate in 1998 was 80%), fraction, or multiple.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Rates and ratios often vary with time, location, particular element (or subset) of a set of objects, etc.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Thus they are often mathematical functions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] A rate (or ratio) may often be thought of as an output-input ratio, benefit-cost ratio, all considered in the broad sense.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, miles per hour in transportation is the output (or benefit) in terms of miles of travel, which one gets from spending an hour (a cost in time) of traveling (at this velocity).
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] A set of sequential indices may be used to enumerate elements (or subsets) of a set of ratios under study.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, in finance, one could define *i* by assigning consecutive integers to companies, to political subdivisions (such as states), to different investments, etc.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] The reason for using indices *i* is so a set of ratios (*i* = 0, *N*) can be used in an equation to calculate a function of the rates such as an average of a set of ratios.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, the average velocity found from the set of *vi*'s mentioned above.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Finding averages may involve using weighted averages and possibly using the harmonic mean.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] A ratio *r* = *a*/*b* has both a numerator *a* and a denominator *b*.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] The value of *a* and *b* may be a real number or integer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] A rate may be equivalently expressed as an inverse of its value if the ratio of its units is also inverse.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, 5 miles (mi) per kilowatt-hour (kWh) corresponds to 1/5 kWh/mi (or 200 Wh/mi).
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Rates are relevant to many aspects of everyday life.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example: *How fast are you driving?* The speed of the car (often expressed in miles per hour) is a rate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] *What interest does your savings account pay you?* The amount of interest paid per year is a rate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] Consider the case where the numerator f of a rate is a function $f(a)$ where a happens to be the denominator of the rate $\delta f/\delta a$ .
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] where *f*(*x*) is the function with respect to *x* over the interval from *a* to *a*+*h*.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] An instantaneous rate of change is equivalent to a derivative.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] For example, the average speed of a car can be calculated using the total distance traveled between two points, divided by the travel time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/rate-mathematics] In contrast, the instantaneous velocity can be determined by viewing a speedometer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] A **service-level objective** (**SLO**) is a target value or range of values for a service level that is measured by an SLI.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] An SLO is a key element of a service-level agreement (SLA) between a service provider and a customer.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] SLOs are agreed upon as a means of measuring the performance of the service provider and are outlined as a way of avoiding disputes between the two parties based on misunderstanding.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] There is often confusion in the use of SLAs and SLOs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] The SLA is the entire agreement that specifies what service is to be provided, how it is supported, times, locations, costs, performance, and responsibilities of the parties involved.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] SLOs are specific measurable characteristics of the SLA such as availability, throughput, frequency, response time, or quality.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] These SLOs together are meant to define the expected service between the provider and the customer and vary depending on the service's urgency, resources, and budget.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] SLOs provide a quantitative means to define the level of service a customer can expect from a provider.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] The SLO are formed by setting goals for metrics (commonly called service level indicators, SLIs).
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] As an example, an availability SLO may be defined as the expected measured value of an availability SLI over a prescribed duration (e.g. four weeks).
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] The availability SLI used will vary based on the nature and architecture of the service.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] For example, a simple web service might use the ratio of successful responses served vs the total number of valid requests received.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] While Andrieux et al. define the SLO as "the quality of service aspect of the agreement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] Syntactically, it is an assertion over the terms of the agreement as well as such qualities as date and time".
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig more concisely define an SLO as "commitment to maintain a particular state of the service in a given period" with respect to the state of the SLA parameters.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig go on to state that while service providers will most often be the lead entity in taking on SLOs there is no firm definition as such and any entity can be responsible for an SLO.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] Optionally an EvaluationEvent maybe assigned to the SLO, an EvaluationEvent is defined as the measure by which the SLO will be checked to see whether it's meeting the expression.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] SLOs should generally be specified in terms of an achievement value or service level, a target measurement, a measurement period, and where and how they are measured.
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] As an example, "90% of calls to the helpdesk should be answered in less than 20 seconds measured over a one-month period as reported by the ACD system".
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] Results can be reported as a percent of time that the target answer time was achieved and then compared to the desired service level (90%).
[src:slo-burn-rate/service-level-objective] The SLO term is found in various scientific papers, for instance in the reference architecture of the SLA@SOI project, and it is used in the Open Grid Forum document on WS-Agreement.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:slo-burn-rate/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
